<!-- SECTION 2: OVERVIEW / INTRO + TL;DR -->
<section class="content-section" id="overview-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Proprietorship to Pvt Ltd Conversion in Delhi - Overview</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-bottom:20px;">
                    <p><strong>&#128204; TL;DR - Proprietorship to Pvt Ltd Conversion Services at a Glance</strong></p>
                    <p>Moving a sole proprietorship to a Private Limited Company in India requires fresh incorporation via SPICe+ under the Companies Act 2013, followed by a Business Takeover Agreement. The transfer can be tax-neutral under Section 47(xiv) of the Income Tax Act 1961 if four conditions are met - assets and liabilities transferred entirely, proprietor holds 50 percent voting power, this is maintained for 5 years and no consideration beyond shares. Patron INR 19,999 fixed.</p>
                </div>
                <p><div class='table-responsive-wrapper'>
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Quick Reference</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Governing Laws</td><td>Company - Companies Act 2013 + Companies (Incorporation) Rules 2014. Tax-Neutral Succession - Section 47(xiv) Income Tax Act 1961 with 4 conditions; Section 115BAA for 22% concessional rate. GST - CGST Act 2017 Notification 12/2017-CT(R) going concern; Rule 41 ITC transfer via Form GST ITC-02</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Applicable To</td><td>Any Delhi sole proprietor able to bring in at least one additional shareholder and one additional director (or one person doubling as both); proprietor must be willing to hold 50% or more voting power for 5 years from incorporation</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Timeline</td><td>End-to-end 15 to 30 days. DSC and DIN 3-5 days; SPICe+ Part A 1-2 days; SPICe+ Part B + AGILE-PRO-S 5-10 days; BTA + GST migration 7-10 days</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Cost (Patron)</td><td>INR 19,999 FIXED (Exl GST and Govt. Charges) - end-to-end SPICe+ + MOA with takeover clause + AOA + BTA + GST migration + compliance kit</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Section 47(xiv) Conditions</td><td>(a) All assets and liabilities transferred entirely; (b) proprietor holds 50% voting power; (c) maintained for 5 years; (d) no consideration other than shares</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Pvt Ltd Minimums</td><td>2 shareholders (cap 200); 2 directors (1 Indian resident under Section 149(3)); no minimum paid-up capital (Companies (Amendment) Act 2015)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Authority</td><td>ROC NCT of Delhi and Haryana, CGO Complex; Central Registration Centre (CRC) for SPICe+ initial scrutiny; CBDT for Section 47(xiv) + 115BAA</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div></p>
                <p>A sole proprietorship - one owner, no separate legal existence, unlimited personal liability, slab-rate taxation - is the right vehicle for a small business but increasingly costly as growth crosses INR 50 lakh to INR 1 crore turnover. The two most common upgrade paths are LLP (lighter compliance but no equity fundraising) and Private Limited Company (heavier compliance but equity fundraising, ESOP, lower 22% corporate tax under Section 115BAA and the institutional credibility needed for VC or PE rounds). The Private Limited route has one specific tax advantage that the LLP route lacks - Section 47(xiv) of the Income Tax Act 1961 makes the transfer of business assets from the proprietor to the company tax-neutral subject to four specific conditions including the proprietor holding at least 50% voting power for 5 years after the succession.</p>
                <p>Content is reviewed quarterly for accuracy.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 3: WHAT IS GSTAT APPEAL FILING -->
<section class="content-section" id="what-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="two-column">
            <div class="column-content">
                <h2 class="section-title">How Proprietorship Actually Becomes a Private Limited Company</h2>
                <div class="content-text what-is-definition">
                    
                    <p>There is NO direct statutory "conversion" of a sole proprietorship into a Private Limited Company under the Companies Act 2013 - Section 366 of the Act provides a conversion pathway only for partnership firms, Limited Liability Partnerships and societies, but NOT for sole proprietorships. This is because a sole proprietorship is not a separate juristic person in Indian law; it is the proprietor in personam, conducting business under a trade name. There is no separate legal entity to "convert".</p>

<p>The Income Tax Act 1961 closes the gap. <strong>Section 47(xiv) treats the succession of a sole proprietorship by a company (registered under the Companies Act) as a non-transfer for capital gains purposes, subject to four cumulative conditions:</strong></p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>(a)</strong> All assets and liabilities of the proprietorship business immediately before succession become the assets and liabilities of the company.</li>
    <li><strong>(b)</strong> The proprietor holds not less than 50 percent of the total voting power in the company.</li>
    <li><strong>(c)</strong> The proprietor continues to hold such 50 percent or more voting power for 5 years from the date of succession.</li>
    <li><strong>(d)</strong> The proprietor does not receive any consideration or benefit, directly or indirectly, other than by way of allotment of shares in the company.</li>
</ul>

<p>In practice, the workflow is - incorporate a fresh Private Limited Company on MCA21 v3 via SPICe+ (with the Memorandum of Association including a takeover clause naming the proprietorship business as a specific object), execute a Business Takeover Agreement transferring assets and liabilities to the new company in exchange for shares to the proprietor (and one additional shareholder for minimum compliance with Section 3 Companies Act 2013) and then migrate GST and other registrations. Where the four Section 47(xiv) conditions are met, the capital gains tax exposure is zero; if any condition fails subsequently (typically the 5-year voting power retention), the gain becomes chargeable in the year of failure under Section 47A.</p>

<p>Delhi anchors this engagement because ROC NCT of Delhi and Haryana at CGO Complex handles all SPICe+ filings and the Central Registration Centre (CRC) provides initial scrutiny. The full set of MCA21 v3 forms - SPICe+ Part A, SPICe+ Part B (INC-32), INC-33 (e-MOA with takeover clause), INC-34 (e-AOA), AGILE-PRO-S, INC-9 - is filed in one integrated workflow.</p>

                </div>
                <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:20px;">
                    <p><strong>Key Terms for Proprietorship to Pvt Ltd Conversion:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Section 47(xiv) Income Tax Act 1961:</strong> Tax-neutral succession of sole proprietorship by a company subject to four cumulative conditions.</p>
<p><strong>Four Conditions:</strong> (a) All assets and liabilities transferred entirely; (b) proprietor holds 50% voting power; (c) maintained for 5 years; (d) no consideration other than shares.</p>
<p><strong>Section 47A:</strong> Breach of any Section 47(xiv) condition - capital gain becomes chargeable in the year of breach.</p>
<p><strong>SPICe+ (INC-32):</strong> Integrated MCA21 v3 e-form covering name reservation (Part A), incorporation (Part B), DIN, PAN, TAN, AGILE-PRO-S.</p>
<p><strong>Takeover Clause in MOA:</strong> Specific object clause naming the proprietorship business in the Memorandum; mandatory; absence is the most common SPICe+ rejection cause.</p>
<p><strong>Business Takeover Agreement (BTA):</strong> Contract transferring proprietorship assets, liabilities, contracts, employees, IP to the company in exchange for shares only.</p>
<p><strong>Section 115BAA:</strong> 22% concessional corporate tax rate (effective ~25.17%); Form 10-IC election; irrevocable.</p>
<p><strong>Section 149(3) Companies Act 2013:</strong> At least one director must be ordinarily resident in India (182+ days in previous FY).</p>
<p><strong>AGILE-PRO-S:</strong> Linked form for GSTIN, EPFO, ESIC, Profession Tax, Bank Account allotment within SPICe+.</p>
<p><strong>Going Concern (GST):</strong> Business transferred as a whole - nil GST under Notification 12/2017-Central Tax (Rate).</p>
<p><strong>Form GST ITC-02:</strong> Transfers unutilised proprietorship ITC to new company GSTIN under Rule 41 CGST Rules 2017.</p>

                </div>
            </div>
