<!-- SECTION 4: WHO CAN FILE -->
<section class="content-section" id="who-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Which Proprietors Should Move to Private Limited (and Which Should Not)</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <p>Moving from proprietorship to Private Limited Company is HIGH-VALUE for the following Delhi-NCR profiles:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Proprietors planning institutional equity fundraising (Series A onwards):</strong> VCs and PE funds typically invest only in Private Limited or LLP-VCC structures, not proprietorships.</li>
                    <li><strong>Proprietors planning ESOP for employees:</strong> Private Limited supports ESOPs through Section 62(1)(b) and Rule 12 of Companies (Share Capital and Debentures) Rules 2014; LLP cannot.</li>
                    <li><strong>Proprietors at INR 1 to 10 crore turnover with effective tax rate above 25%:</strong> Section 115BAA at 22% (effective ~25.17%) is meaningfully lower than the proprietor's slab marginal rate.</li>
                    <li><strong>Proprietors planning eventual IPO or strategic acquisition:</strong> Exit at Private Limited stage is institutional-grade; subsequent conversion to Public Limited (Section 18 Companies Act 2013) is straightforward.</li>
                    <li><strong>Proprietors needing corporate-grade B2B credibility:</strong> PSU tenders, large corporate purchase orders and government contracts often have minimum entity requirements that proprietorships fail.</li>
                    <li><strong>Proprietors willing to hold 50% voting power for 5 years:</strong> So they can claim Section 47(xiv) tax neutrality on the business transfer.</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top:16px;"><strong>NOT optimal for:</strong> Proprietors at INR 25-50 lakh turnover with no fundraising or ESOP plans (LLP route cheaper, lighter compliance, avoids statutory audit); proprietors planning exit within 3 years (5-year voting power lock-in becomes a constraint); proprietors who cannot identify a second trusted shareholder; proprietors with significant accumulated business losses wanting to set off against personal income (corporate losses do not flow to individual shareholders); proprietors with significant standalone capital asset transfers that may still be taxable outside Section 47(xiv).</p>

            </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

