<!-- SECTION 8: DOCUMENTS REQUIRED -->
<section class="content-section" id="documents-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Documents Checklist for Proprietorship-to-Pvt-Ltd Move</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <ul>
                    <li>PAN and Aadhaar of the proprietor and the second shareholder / director</li>
                    <li>Passport-size photographs of both directors</li>
                    <li>Residential address proof of both directors and shareholders (electricity bill / bank statement under 2 months)</li>
                    <li>Email IDs and Indian mobile numbers (for OTP-based MCA verification)</li>
                    <li>Proprietorship business existence proof - GST certificate, Shop and Establishment licence, Udyam / MSME registration</li>
                    <li>Last 2-3 years financial statements of the proprietorship (Balance Sheet and Profit and Loss)</li>
                    <li>Last 2-3 years Income Tax Returns of the proprietor (ITR-3 or ITR-4 as applicable)</li>
                    <li>List of all assets, liabilities, contracts and employees of the proprietorship as on the proposed takeover effective date</li>
                    <li>CA-certified business valuation report (Patron coordinates this through panel valuers if not already available)</li>
                    <li>Existing GST registration certificate, IEC, FSSAI and other regulatory licences of the proprietorship</li>
                    <li>Delhi registered office proof for the new company - rent agreement, NOC from owner, latest utility bill</li>
                    <li>Three proposed company names (in case the first is taken or requires referral)</li>
                    <li>Bank statements of the proprietorship for the last 6 months (for valuation continuity and bank account opening)</li>
                    <li>Self-declaration of the proprietor confirming readiness to hold 50% voting power for 5 years (internal document for Section 47(xiv) defence file)</li>
                </ul>

            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- SECTION 9: CHALLENGES -->
<section class="content-section" id="challenges-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Common Challenges and Patron Solutions</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="table-responsive-wrapper">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Impact</th><th>How Patron Accounting Solves It</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Section 47(xiv) 5-year voting power lock-in</td><td>If the proprietor reduces shareholding below 50% voting power within 5 years of succession (sale to co-founder, dilution from fundraising, exit), the capital gains exemption is revoked retrospectively under Section 47A in the year of breach.</td><td>Patron computes the realistic fundraising or co-founder dilution plan over 5 years at engagement start. Where institutional dilution will breach the 50% threshold, options include - delaying conversion, structuring initial share allotment so subsequent dilution does not breach (Section 43 dual-class shares with weighted voting plus AOA flexibility) or accepting the slump sale tax cost upfront with Section 115BAA election for the 22% rate.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>MOA takeover clause omission</td><td>The SINGLE most common SPICe+ rejection cause for proprietor-to-Pvt-Ltd cases is the absence of a specific takeover clause naming the proprietorship business in the MOA objects.</td><td>Patron's drafting includes a properly worded takeover clause as a primary object: "To take over the existing sole proprietorship business of [Proprietor Name] under the trade name [Trade Name], including all its assets, liabilities, contracts and employees, on such terms and conditions as the Board of Directors may decide." This wording aligns with Section 47(xiv) requirements and is accepted by ROC NCT of Delhi and Haryana.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>CA-certified business valuation</td><td>Many proprietors do not have a recent valuation; the share allotment must be supported by independent valuation, especially where intangible assets or goodwill are material.</td><td>Patron coordinates with panel valuers (Registered Valuers under Section 247 of Companies Act 2013 where applicable, or independent CAs for non-mandatory cases). Valuation methodology - net asset value plus reasonable goodwill multiple - documented to withstand assessment scrutiny.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Section 115BAA election timing</td><td>The election via Form 10-IC must be filed before the due date of the first ITR; once made, it is IRREVOCABLE; mid-year incorporation creates timing questions.</td><td>For mid-year SPICe+ incorporations, Patron recommends Section 115BAA election only after confirming the company will not need SEZ deductions, Section 35AD investment-linked deductions, additional depreciation or specified incentives - all forfeited under Section 115BAA. The election is calendared with the first ITR due date.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>GST migration timing and ITC transfer</td><td>The new company GSTIN is issued during SPICe+ via AGILE-PRO-S, BEFORE the BTA effective date; if business operations transfer to the new GSTIN before the BTA is executed, transactions may have characterisation issues.</td><td>Patron sequences tightly - new company GSTIN issued, BTA executed with effective date aligned with the first invoice issued under company name, proprietorship GSTIN cancelled with effective date matching BTA, Form GST ITC-02 filed transferring unutilised credit. Bridge transactions are categorised correctly.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Identifying a trustworthy second shareholder</td><td>While a Private Limited needs only 2 shareholders, the choice matters because the second shareholder participates in governance and the proprietor's 50% voting power must be maintained for 5 years.</td><td>Patron typically structures the second shareholder as a family member with minimal holding (e.g., 0.1% to maintain 99.9% with the proprietor) or a trusted co-founder where genuine joint ownership is intended. AOA drafted with reasonable founder pre-emption rights and Section 43 dual-class structure where helpful.</td></tr>

