<!-- SECTION 15A: LEGAL FRAMEWORK -->
<section class="content-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Legal and Compliance Framework</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <p><strong>Company Governing Statute:</strong> Companies Act 2013.</p>
                <p><strong>Company Procedural Rules:</strong> Companies (Incorporation) Rules 2014 + Companies (Share Capital and Debentures) Rules 2014.</p>
                <p><strong>Regulatory Status of Proprietorship-to-Company:</strong> No direct statutory conversion route under Companies Act 2013 (Section 366 covers firm, LLP and society only); however, fresh incorporation under Section 3 read with SPICe+ followed by Business Takeover Agreement is recognised by both MCA and Income Tax Department.</p>
                <p><strong>Tax-Neutrality Provision:</strong> Section 47(xiv) of Income Tax Act 1961 - succession of a sole proprietorship by a company is NOT a transfer subject to four conditions: (a) all assets and liabilities of the proprietorship immediately before succession become the assets and liabilities of the company; (b) proprietor holds not less than 50% of total voting power in the company; (c) such 50% holding is continued for 5 years from the date of succession; (d) proprietor does not receive any consideration or benefit other than allotment of shares in the company.</p>
                <p><strong>Breach of Section 47(xiv) Conditions:</strong> Where any of the four conditions is breached subsequently (typically the 5-year 50% voting power retention), the capital gain on the original transfer becomes chargeable in the year of breach in the hands of the company; documented through Section 47A.</p>
                <p><strong>Concessional Corporate Tax Rate:</strong> Section 115BAA Income Tax Act 1961 - 22% (plus surcharge and cess; effective ~25.17%); election via Form 10-IC before the due date of the first ITR; election is IRREVOCABLE; forfeits SEZ deductions, Section 35AD investment-linked deductions, additional depreciation, MAT credit and certain other incentives.</p>
                <p><strong>Private Limited Company Requirements:</strong> Minimum 2 shareholders (cap of 200); Minimum 2 directors (1 Indian resident under Section 149(3) - stayed in India 182 days or more in previous FY); no minimum paid-up capital (Companies (Amendment) Act 2015 removed the INR 1 lakh minimum); registered office in India.</p>
                <p><strong>MOA Takeover Clause:</strong> The Memorandum of Association must include a specific object clause for the takeover of the proprietorship business; absence is the most common SPICe+ rejection cause for proprietor-to-Pvt-Ltd cases.</p>
                <p><strong>SPICe+ Forms (MCA21 v3):</strong> SPICe+ Part A (name reservation); SPICe+ Part B / INC-32 (incorporation); INC-33 (e-MOA with takeover clause); INC-34 (e-AOA); AGILE-PRO-S (GSTIN, EPFO, ESIC, Profession Tax, Bank Account); INC-9 (subscriber declaration).</p>
                <p><strong>Post-Incorporation Forms:</strong> PAS-3 (return of allotment of shares to subscribers); ADT-1 (auditor appointment within 30 days of first board meeting); DIR-12 (director particulars); INC-22 (registered office where different from incorporation address); Form 10-IC (Section 115BAA election); Form 3CEA (where slump sale character applies for any non-Section-47(xiv) component).</p>
                <p><strong>Business Valuation:</strong> CA-certified business valuation for share allotment; Registered Valuer under Section 247 Companies Act 2013 mandatory in specified cases (e.g., shares issued for non-cash consideration to a non-related party); for related-party transfers, CA valuation suffices.</p>
                <p><strong>GST Statute - Going Concern:</strong> CGST Act 2017 - Notification 12/2017-Central Tax (Rate) provides nil GST rate on services by way of transfer of a going concern.</p>
                <p><strong>GST ITC Transfer:</strong> Rule 41 CGST Rules 2017 - transfer of unutilised Input Tax Credit via Form GST ITC-02 on transfer of business as a going concern.</p>
                <p><strong>Stamp Duty:</strong> Indian Stamp Act 1899 read with Delhi Stamp Schedule - on MOA, AOA and Business Takeover Agreement; on the BTA, stamp duty depends on whether immovable property is included (conveyance duty) or only movables (lower stamp duty).</p>
                <p><strong>Annual Compliance:</strong> AGM within 6 months of FY end; AOC-4 within 30 days of AGM; MGT-7 within 60 days of AGM; DPT-3 by 30 June; DIR-3 KYC by 30 September; statutory audit MANDATORY regardless of turnover; ITR by 31 October if audited (31 July otherwise).</p>
                <p><strong>Authority - Company:</strong> Registrar of Companies (ROC), NCT of Delhi and Haryana, CGO Complex, Lodhi Road, New Delhi 110003; Central Registration Centre (CRC) for SPICe+ initial scrutiny.</p>
                <p><strong>Authority for source verification:</strong> MCA21 v3 at <a href="https://www.mca.gov.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">mca.gov.in</a>, CBDT at <a href="https://www.incometaxindia.gov.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">incometaxindia.gov.in</a>, CBIC GST at <a href="https://cbic-gst.gov.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">cbic-gst.gov.in</a> and India Code (statutes) at <a href="https://www.indiacode.nic.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">indiacode.nic.in</a>.</p>

            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

