                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How do you convert a sole proprietorship to a Private Limited Company in India?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Two main phases. Phase One - incorporate a fresh Private Limited Company on MCA21 v3 via SPICe+ (INC-32) with at least 2 shareholders and 2 directors (one Indian resident); MOA must include a specific takeover clause naming the proprietorship business in the objects. Phase Two - execute a Business Takeover Agreement transferring assets and liabilities in exchange for shares; structure to satisfy Section 47(xiv) conditions; migrate GST and other registrations.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-2">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is Section 47(xiv) and what are the conditions?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Section 47(xiv) of the Income Tax Act 1961 treats the succession of a sole proprietorship by a company as a non-transfer for capital gains. Four conditions must be met cumulatively - (a) all assets and liabilities transferred entirely; (b) proprietor holds at least 50 percent total voting power; (c) such 50 percent holding maintained for 5 years from succession; (d) proprietor receives no consideration other than shares.</p></div>
