                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Patron Accounting charges INR 19,999 (Exl GST and Govt. Charges) for end-to-end execution in Delhi - covering DSC for two directors, SPICe+ filing with MOA (including takeover clause) and AOA, Business Takeover Agreement, GST migration with Form GST ITC-02, Section 115BAA election, primary licence transitions (Udyam and Shop Act) and post-incorporation compliance kit. Statutory charges (MCA SPICe+ fee per authorised capital, Delhi stamp duty, DSC vendor, valuation) are pass-through.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-4">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How long does it take to convert proprietorship to Private Limited Company?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>End-to-end timeline is 15 to 30 days for standard cases. DSC and DIN 3-5 working days; SPICe+ Part A name reservation 1-3 days; SPICe+ Part B incorporation 5-10 working days; Business Takeover Agreement and GST migration 7-10 working days; sectoral licence re-registrations vary - Udyam and Shop Act 3-7 days, FSSAI 30-60 days, IEC 5-10 days. CA-certified business valuation adds 5-10 working days.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-5">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the tax treatment of converting proprietorship to Pvt Ltd?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>If all four Section 47(xiv) conditions are met (assets and liabilities transferred entirely; proprietor holds 50 percent voting power; this is maintained 5 years; no consideration other than shares), the transfer is tax-neutral - zero capital gains exposure. If any condition fails subsequently, the capital gain becomes chargeable in the year of failure under Section 47A. Section 115BAA election allows 22 percent concessional rate (effective ~25.17 percent) post-conversion.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-6">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Does GST need to be re-registered when proprietorship becomes a Pvt Ltd?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Yes. The Private Limited Company is a new legal entity and obtains a fresh GSTIN through AGILE-PRO-S during SPICe+ incorporation itself. The proprietorship GSTIN is cancelled via Form GST REG-16. Unutilised Input Tax Credit transfers via Form GST ITC-02 under Rule 41 of the CGST Rules 2017. The transfer of business as a going concern attracts nil GST under Notification 12/2017-Central Tax (Rate).</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-7">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the minimum capital and number of directors for a Pvt Ltd?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>No minimum paid-up capital is required (Companies (Amendment) Act 2015 removed the earlier INR 1 lakh minimum). Minimum 2 shareholders and 2 directors are required under Section 3 and Section 149 of the Companies Act 2013 respectively. At least 1 director must be an Indian resident under Section 149(3) - i.e., stayed in India for at least 182 days during the previous financial year.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-8">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Why is the MOA takeover clause critical for proprietorship-to-Pvt-Ltd cases?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>The Memorandum of Association must include a specific object clause naming the proprietorship business to be taken over by the new company. This is mandatory both for Section 47(xiv) succession treatment and for ROC acceptance. The absence of a properly worded takeover clause is the single most common SPICe+ rejection cause for proprietor-to-Pvt-Ltd cases at ROC NCT of Delhi and Haryana. Patron drafts this clause precisely the first time.</p></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Quick Answers -->
            <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:32px;">
                <p><strong>Quick Answers</strong></p>
                <p><strong>Q: Mechanism?</strong> A: Fresh Private Limited Company incorporation via SPICe+ + Business Takeover Agreement (no direct statutory conversion under Companies Act 2013).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Tax-neutral provision?</strong> A: Section 47(xiv) Income Tax Act 1961 - 4 conditions including 50% voting power for 5 years.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Minimum shareholders / directors?</strong> A: 2 shareholders + 2 directors (1 Indian resident under Section 149(3)).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Minimum paid-up capital?</strong> A: No minimum (Companies (Amendment) Act 2015 removed the INR 1 lakh floor).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Core MCA form?</strong> A: SPICe+ (INC-32) on MCA21 v3 with INC-33 (e-MOA with takeover clause), INC-34, AGILE-PRO-S, INC-9.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Concessional corporate tax?</strong> A: Section 115BAA - 22% (effective ~25.17%); Form 10-IC election; IRREVOCABLE.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: GST migration?</strong> A: New GSTIN via AGILE-PRO-S; Form GST ITC-02 for ITC transfer; going concern nil GST under Notification 12/2017-CT(R).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Stamp duty?</strong> A: Per Delhi state Schedule under Indian Stamp Act 1899 - on MOA, AOA and Business Takeover Agreement.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Timeline?</strong> A: 15 to 30 days end to end.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: 5-year voting power lock-in?</strong> A: Proprietor must hold at least 50% voting power for 5 years from succession; breach revokes Section 47(xiv) and triggers capital gains in the year of breach under Section 47A.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Statutory audit?</strong> A: MANDATORY for Private Limited regardless of turnover.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Breach treatment?</strong> A: Section 47A - capital gain chargeable in the year of breach in the hands of the company.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: ESOP possible?</strong> A: Yes - Section 62(1)(b) + Rule 12 Companies (Share Capital and Debentures) Rules 2014.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Patron fee?</strong> A: INR 19,999 FIXED for end-to-end move including SPICe+, BTA, GST migration and compliance kit.</p>

            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

